# Test after build and run

Before asking the user to test the application (EXE or in-browser UI):

1. **Build an updated EXE** if the project has a PyInstaller spec (e.g. `PRTG_Analyzer.spec`): run the build from repo root. The spec produces a one-file EXE with version in the filename (`dist/PyPRTG_CLA_v{version}.exe`). For release packaging (minimal zip: exe, apply-update.bat, README.md, manual.html), use `.\build-and-release.ps1`.
2. **Run the app** (either the newly built EXE or `python run_analyzer.py` from `source/`) so it is already running when you hand off to the user.
3. **Then** ask the user to test (e.g. open http://127.0.0.1:8077 and try the flow).

Do not ask the user to "please test the EXE" or "run the app and test" without having built and started it first.

## Proper restart for manual testing

After backend or frontend changes, a **proper restart** is required or the UI may still behave like the old code (e.g. slider charts not updating).

- **Stop any existing process** on the app port (e.g. 8077) before starting, e.g. PowerShell: `Get-NetTCPConnection -LocalPort 8077 -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | ForEach-Object { Stop-Process -Id $_.OwningProcess -Force -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue }`.
- **Start the app fresh** from `source/`: `python run_analyzer.py` (run in background so it stays up).
- If you changed only frontend JS/CSS, tell the user to **hard refresh** the browser (Ctrl+F5 or Ctrl+Shift+R) so cached scripts are not used.
- After restart, have the user **re-upload** the log/file if they are re-testing; in-memory caches are cleared on restart.
